CALM has been restored to the Lebombo border control between Mozambique and Mzansi. This follows reports of overcrowding and congestion last week, with people testing positive for Covid-19 while others presented false Covid-19 test results. According to port manager Obed Maditsi, the number of positive Covid-19 cases stood at 53 on Saturday, which was allegedly said to be increasing daily. Maditsi said most of the people who were at the port of entry travelled back home. He said infrastructure at the border was limited and unable to accommodate many travellers. And with Covid-19 pandemic protocols such as screening and testing, employees were forced to work at a limited pace. He said management took the approach to process people in categories, separating South Africans and non-South Africans, men from women and the vulnerable to avoid a stampede. Meanwhile, the Limpopo health department called on those coming to South Africa through the Beitbridge border post to self-quarantine before interacting with others upon arrival at their destinations. Limpopo health spokesman Thilivhali Muavha said 104 people tested positive at the port of entry during the past four days, before Friday, 8 January. He said with thousands of people stuck at the port for days, the department was worried that the events at the border were fast becoming a super spreader. “Considering the incubation period of the virus, we wish to implore those who will be crossing from Beit­bridge to do the right thing and self-quarantine because they have been exposed to a potential super spreader,” he told the People’s Paper